edu.spa.ftclib.util

Class ClassRegistrar

  • java.lang.Object
    • edu.spa.ftclib.util.ClassRegistrar

  • public class ClassRegistrar
extends java.lang.Object
    Created by Gabriel on 2018-01-04. May be used to register an op-mode class marked with com.qualcomm.robotcore.eventloop.opmode.Autonomous or com.qualcomm.robotcore.eventloop.opmode.TeleOp. Automatically gets the op-mode name and group.

    We use this to test our samples, which we must disable (with com.qualcomm.robotcore.eventloop.opmode.Disabled) so they don't all automatically install for you. Unless you have a special case like that, you probably shouldn't use this class; you should just not disable the op-modes you want to run and let FTC's code automatically register them.

    To use, go to FtcOpModeRegister.java in FtcRobotController -> java -> org.firstinspires.ftc.robotcontroller -> internal. In the register method, create a new ClassRegistrar with the given OpModeManager. Then you can call registerClass(java.lang.Class<OpMode>) for each op-mode class you want to enable. If you want to enable a whole package, use PackageRegistrar.

    Inspired by org.firstinspires.ftc.robotcore.internal.opmode.AnnotatedOpModeClassFilter.

    • Method Detail

      • registerClass

        public void registerClass(java.lang.Class<OpMode> clazz)
        Register a given class as an op-mode. The class must extend OpMode, but other than that it is assumed you have made sure it is actually a valid op-mode. The com.qualcomm.robotcore.eventloop.opmode.Disabled annotation is ignored. If the class does not have a TeleOp or Autonomous annotation, the op-mode is registered as tele-op.
        Parameters:
        clazz - The class to register
